Being autistic and perpetually gnc plus very sexual and other ‚Äúmasculine‚Äù type things made me not relate to being a woman at all. Rejecting femininity in every way and feeling alien in this world made me think it would be easier to be a male. Add on severe depression, ptsd, a d being suicidal and I had an identity crisis. Add on to that being led on by multiple gay men and falling in love with them and hating myself for not being attractive to them and that‚Äôs how I ended up being trans. I ended up detransitioning four years later when I realized that even after top surgery and hormones that I felt no better about myself, that I was actually getting worse, and that I didn‚Äôt need to pretend to be a man in order to be myself. I realized very clearly how my trauma and self hate causes me to desire an escape and a molding into a new person who I thought would be a better version of me, instead, i was actually a worse version, hating my body and sex, resenting my sexuality and reality. Realized it was a big charade and that I could be valid as a gnc woman, I just needed to practice some radical self love and acceptance. I used to cry about hating my genitals and stuff Now I am so happy just being a woman because I realize that my body is there for me, it‚Äôs healthy and normal. And I was never really supposed to be a man, or be trans, I just thought transition could help my depression and self hate. Instead, actual therapy, mindfulness, and self love have helped my depression and self esteem. I no longer am jealous of men or want to be a gay man because I realized that I am my body, I am my sex, I am my genitalia, and I wouldn‚Äôt be me without those things, and trying to be something else was unnatural and irrational. People think I‚Äôm a guy sometimes but I don‚Äôt care if they think I‚Äôm a man or a woman because I‚Äôm secure with my sex now, unlike in the past when I was extremely insecure and constantly worried about being masculine enough or passing or whatever. 
Short answer: I was trans because of mental illness trauma and identity confusion due to being autistic and a weird girl. And I stopped being trans because I put in the work in therapy and accepted myself for what I am; a weird mentally ill girl.

It does feel very frustrating at times. Nobody bothers to actually read up and investigate the matters, so no one knows what they‚Äôre on about. They‚Äôre not thinking critically. But I assure you that there are tons of lgb, especially lesbians who fully agree with you. There are many Facebook groups, people on twitter, tumblr, etc. little groups of mutuals who keep each other sane. It‚Äôs harder in real life circles. I don‚Äôt keep my views hidden from anybody. The truth is that the reason people get angry with gender critical views is that they are scared that they are invalidated some how. They are insecure. It‚Äôs not your fault that they aren‚Äôt in a good place to think critically about it. Lots of people lose friends over that stuff. It‚Äôs probably best not to provoke your friends. But you can state your views in language that is less offensive to them, more neutral and rational. If you did bring it up, have a mature and genuine discussion. Don‚Äôt even bring up the term radical feminism. Most people agree with radfem beliefs to some extent but they get turned off at the associations with it. To say that you should be allowed to choose your sexual partners as a freedom of sexual choice, vs that you don‚Äôt think trans women are women is an example of how to remain more neutral. Of course, a lot of times the beliefs grow and you might get passionate about them. In general I will speak my mind and anyone in my life knows that. If they actually care about you they will respect your beliefs but you also must be open to their beliefs too. Tolerating them. I don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs good to keep major secrets but it‚Äôs true that it‚Äôs a huge risk to fully state your beliefs. A lot of people get dumped by their friends. It‚Äôs due to their personal insecurities. ü§∑ the thing is that I have my own demons. I‚Äôm not going to placate anybody else‚Äôs in spite of mine. I do find that friends tend to be more rational and nuanced than random people online so if you do mention anything just be personal about it aka don‚Äôt state rhetoric just state how it effects you personally and they hopefully would understand enough just as you understand their position enough. That is if you ever want to talk to them honestly about it.

Non-binary doesn‚Äôt actually mean anything concrete. It‚Äôs basically an abstract way to say that you don‚Äôt like gender norms and are probably quirky. Therefore non binary people don‚Äôt face any discrimination except for well deserved joking about it online on occasion. However, there are some people who transition who ID as non-binary. So those people could potentially have some issues. They could have some mental health issues with gender dysphoria, but unless they actually transition they face no discrimination. Unless the ‚Äúdiscrimination‚Äù they mean is having to acknowledge that they‚Äôre either male or female on a legal form or some bullshit. Most of the time the ‚Äúdiscrimination‚Äù is just society being rational and not indulging their abstract feeling of the social construct of gender, or people refusing to use they/them pronouns, which isn‚Äôt discrimination, it‚Äôs (using he or she) is just social shorthand for describing men and women. I think non-binary identity is a joke. I understand the urge to try and get away from restrictive gender constructs, but pretending you are ‚Äúsomething else‚Äù besides male or female either ‚Äúinternally‚Äù or physically is absurd. Just be a non conforming male or female. That‚Äôs far more radical than pretending you don‚Äôt have a sex or that you are somehow enlightened by living ‚Äúbeyond‚Äù gender with meaningless abstract gender labels suited to fit every individual and which thus mean nothing outside of a cute nickname type of thing. ‚ÄúGenderstar‚Äù etc etc

Yeah I don‚Äôt know how I feel about my own top surgery. Well, I do know, I hate it and regret it, but I mean the surgeon himself. He was a plastic surgeon who practiced trans stuff too. He was a very nice and caring guy, he did seem genuinely concerned about my mental health. But at the same time, it was quite irresponsible to perform that surgery on a healthy body. But the thing is that he did require two letters of recommendation  from doctors first, so he was trying to follow the accepted guidelines for trans patients. I feel like I can‚Äôt really blame the guy for trying to make money. I‚Äôd probably do the same if I thought I was following the proper guidelines. I feel much more angry at the many therapists who were unhelpful, the general practitioner who wrote one letter of recommendation who barely even knew me, and my psychiatrist who knew I was fucked up and suicidal and had all these issues and still deemed me stable enough to make a surgical decision like that. I feel like none of these doctors know what‚Äôs really going on and they‚Äôre all just listening to the transpoganda forcing everyone to just blindly validate it. Idk. Sometimes I think about contacting the surgeons office maybe anonymously and writing all this but I‚Äôm scared of being dismissed. And the general doctor too, I still see her. I feel I should say something. My former psychiatrist died so I can‚Äôt tell her but so far I just don‚Äôt feel comfortable doing it, or I haven‚Äôt had the opportunity to bring attention to it. If they asked a survey or something online that didn‚Äôt require direct contact id probably talk about detransition but so far it‚Äôs a little much for me.

I don‚Äôt really approve of cosmetic surgery but I also think that it‚Äôs a persons right to have it if it‚Äôs safe to do. Unfortunately, they aren‚Äôt calling trans surgery what it really is-cosmetic surgery. They‚Äôre calling it ‚Äúhealth care‚Äù getting it covered by insurance, and it‚Äôs ridiculous. My opinion is, it‚Äôs your body, if you‚Äôre an adult go fuck with it how you want, but don‚Äôt pretend it‚Äôs health care, and dont make taxpayers contribute to it. And especially do not allow children to have it done.

You know, I know a TIM who is a gay man but also is AGP too. I don‚Äôt really understand it. I for one though, do not support transition for any reason unless it‚Äôs for physical safety (example, a woman pretending to be a man in order to escape male predators). I think that regardless of the misogyny or sexism inherent in transition, it‚Äôs really just a pretty mentally unhealthy thing to do for anybody. To deny ones body is to deny both reality and ones self. You can‚Äôt separate the body and mind since the brain is part of the body. Thus, to pretend to be the opposite sex is to deny yourself, and reality. Denying reality is never a healthy thing to do. It‚Äôs irrational or straight up delusional. From a mental health perspective, it‚Äôs damaging to pretend to be something you aren‚Äôt, hate yourself own body, and surgically change it, or even desire to change it. So no, I don‚Äôt approve of TIMS (or TIFS) transitioning even for non fetish  reasons.

Well, most people feel the same way, I know I did at that age. I was so suicidal for years I never thought about the future. Most people don‚Äôt know what they really want to do. If they say they do they are likely to change their mind later on. So don‚Äôt feel weird about that. 

The first thing to do is to A LOT of self reflection. What clubs or activities did you do in your school years? As a kid? What are your hobbies or interests? What do you hate doing? What are your best subjects and worst subjects? You can cross out options easier than not to eliminate things. I eliminated math science and physical labor straight away and knew I wanted to avoid those. 

Next, take a variety of career and personality tests. The big five, enneagram, Myers Briggs, etc etc etc. Not only are they fun, but they can tell you things about yourself. If you consistently get labeled with a certain type of intelligence, be aware of that. Career inventories are cool because they will take your personality traits and interests and recommend specific fields jobs and majors based on them. More sophisticated tests will tell you specifics of those jobs, their requirements, the schooling needed, and average salaries. You can find a variety of these tests online, or maybe your school offers some too. Explore those. 

Then, try to eliminate different types of colleges. Theirs a regular university with liberal arts in which you will be required to take a breadth of courses in different areas. Those can be useful for when you want to try different things and see if you like them or not. Then there‚Äôs specific colleges for the arts or theater. Obviously those will be focused more on varying types of creativity and artistry and less on traditional liberal arts courses. Or maybe a trade school? Where they are less focused on arts or an overview of many traditional courses and focus on a very specific skill or labor. Usually those require fewer years in school to complete. Try to narrow it down to one of those types of colleges and you can then explore the programs of that type at various ones. 

Finally, keep these things in mind. The job you have now or get during school won‚Äôt be your job forever. Don‚Äôt feel pressured to stick with something you don‚Äôt care about just because you have experience or are familiar with it. Go in with an open mind and explore different areas to learn more while completing your requirements. Don‚Äôt declare any major right away even though you will be pressured to. Remain undecided for a year or two if need be. Most people change their major anyway once or twice. Also, try to network while you do it by getting friendly with various students clubs teachers internships etc so you have more opportunities in the future once you do graduate doing whatever. 

I wish I had done all these things at your age. But I was too depressed to care so I ended up going to the main liberal arts college by my home with no plans at all. After four years of being undecided and unhappy I finally realized I should have gone to art school right away, and I joined the art program at my college last semester. I‚Äôm going to be a few years late graduating but it‚Äôs well worth it to pursue my passions for a long term career in what I truly care about.

Also, it‚Äôs very hard to avoid the capitalist struggle of work. Just try to play the system when you can and maybe find an easy part time job on campus while you‚Äôre in school to get experience and make a little money. If you find the right career suited for your abilities, personality, education level, interests, and general needs, then it makes working for most of your life at least sometimes rewarding. Don‚Äôt forget to network and not burn bridges if you can too so that when you graduate with a degree you aren‚Äôt totally lost at what to do with it or where to work.

Hiding pain is no help. It‚Äôs only convenient to employers to let their employees hide their pain so they don‚Äôt have to deal with it or acknowledge it.
